8","1 October 1000":"1 October 1000","0998":"0998","Llannefydd, Denbighshire, Wales":"Llannefydd, Denbighshire, Wales","Dyffryn Clwyd, Denbighshire, Wales":"Denbighshire, Wales, United Kingdom","Wales":"Wales","Iâl, Denbighshire, Wales":"Denbighshire, Wales","Efenechtid, Denbighshire, Wales":"Efenechtyd, Denbighshire, Wales, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"ap","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Hungarian Geza, Jeno, Arpad, Attila, Csaba.","Hungarian: variant of   Papp  , meaning ‘priest (of the Catholic or Orthodox Church)’. This surname is also found in Romania, Slovakia, Croatia, and Serbia, and also among Rusyns (in Serbia and Croatia). See also   Pop   2 and   Popa  .","English: variant of   Pape   1."],"variants":[{"name":"Papp","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Hungarian Laszlo, Zoltan, Geza, Istvan, Gabor, Miklos, Tibor, Arpad, Denes, Imre, Attila.","German (Bavaria, Tyrol): from Middle High German <i>pap</i> ‘baby food’, Dutch <i>pap</i> ‘porridge, pap’, hence perhaps a nickname denoting someone who had lost his teeth or subsisted on a meager diet.","Hungarian: from <i>pap</i> ‘priest (of the Catholic or Orthodox Church)’, probably an occupational name for someone in the service of a priest or a nickname for a pious person. This surname is also found in Romania and Slovakia, and also among Rusyns. Compare   Pap   and   Pop  ."]}]},{"name":"Marchan","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Spanish Jose, Juan, Andres, Evaristo, Francisco, Jesus, Nonito, Ramon, Alejandra, Arturo, Atanacio, Audilia.","Spanish (<b>Marchán</b>): variant of <b>Merchán</b> ‘merchant, dealer’ (see   Merchan   and French   Marchand  )."],"variants":[{"name":"Merchan","meanings":["Spanish (<b>Merchán</b>): occupational name from <i>merchán</i> ‘merchant, dealer’, from Old French <i>merchant</i> (see   Marchand  )."]}]},{"name":"Rhys","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Traditional name meaning ‘ardour’; borne in the Middle Ages by various rulers in south-west Wales, including  Rhys ap Tewdur  (  d. 1093 ) and  Rhys ap Gruffudd  (  1132–97 )."],"variants":[{"name":"Reece","meanings":["Anglicized spelling of Rhys . The name is now in widespread and frequent use outside Wales, in many cases representing a transferred use of the surname so spelled, which is derived from the given name."]},{"name":"Rees","meanings":["Anglicized spelling of Welsh Rhys, in some cases representing a transferred use of the surname so spelled, which is derived from the Welsh given name."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Rhys ap Marchan of Dyffryn Clwyd was born on 1 August 0960, in Denbighshire, Wales, his father, Marchan \"Marchweithian\" ap Cynwrig, was 31 and his mother, Mrs. Marchan ap Cynwrig, was 21. He had at least 2 daughters with Mrs. Rhys Ap Marchan. He died on 6 February 1026, in Efenechtyd, Denbighshire, Wales, United Kingdom, at the age of 65."},"et":{"1 August 0960–06 Feb 1026":"1. august 0960–6. veebruar 1026","0960–1026":"0960–1026","0985–Female":"0985–Surnud","0998–1020":"0998–1020","1000–1036":"1000–1036","0930–1021":"0930–1021","0940–Female":"0940–Surnud","1 August 0960":"1. august 0960","1000":"1000","1021":"1021","1020":"1020","0930":"0930","0985":"0985","06 Feb 1026":"6. veebruar 1026","0940":"0940","1026":"1026","1036":"1036","0960":"0960","about 0998":"umbes 0998","1 October 1000":"1. oktoober 1000","0998":"0998","Llannefydd, Denbighshire, Wales":"Llannefydd, Denbighshire, Wales","Dyffryn Clwyd, Denbighshire, Wales":"Denbighshire, Wales, United Kingdom","Wales":"Wales","Iâl, Denbighshire, Wales":"Denbighshire, Wales","Efenechtid, Denbighshire, Wales":"Efenechtyd, Denbighshire, Wales, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1 August 0960–06 Feb 1026":"1. elokuuta 0960–6. 